Additional details

Control Your Comfort and Your Color Scheme, or use your tablet or computer. All you need is a Wi-Fi connection, or use the free app for smartphone/tablet to manage thermostat remotely and take advantage of savings when away and maintain comfort when home. Simple setup takes the hassle out of programming your thermostat. You can also control thermostat using the touch screen and change the background color to match your paint color or personal preference. Your RTH9585WF features flexible seven day programming, energy savings mode, an indoor humidity sensor, and voice command through the Total Connect Comfort app.

From the manufacturer

Custom Color Display

Features

  • Customizable Color Touchscreen
  • Monthly Energy Reports
  • Smart Response Learning
  • Utility Rebate Eligible

  • Check with your energy provider about available energy savings rebates.

One of the most unique features of the Wi-Fi Smart Color Thermostat is the color display. Change it to match or accent your décor. And then change your mind whenever you want.

The bright, high-definition display features smart controls and shows the current conditions, forecasts, and more.

Plus, you can view daily weather forecast for your home on the display screen and check indoor and outdoor humidity.

  • Gain further control over your home from anywhere, anytime when you access the Wi-Fi Smart Color Thermostat through the Total Connect Comfort App.
  • Easily connect your Wi-Fi thermostat with compatible voice assistant devices like Amazon Alexa, Google Assistant, Microsoft Cortana, and more.
  • Learns your home's heating & cooling cycles to help get the right temperature when you want it.
  • Get alerts when it's time to change your filters and when temperatures get too high or low.

IS YOUR HOME COMPATIBLE? Identify your home's voltage. Only low voltage systems are compatible with Honeywell Home Smart Thermostats. Here are some signs you have a low voltage system:

Do you have low voltage in your home?

  • Your home has a furnace in the basement, garage, bathroom, etc.
  • You either have central air conditioning, a heat pump, boiler or split system.
  • Your home contains heating vents along the floors of your rooms.
  • Changing your thermostat affects multiple rooms.

Is your wiring compatible?

Power off your system by using a switch or turning off power at the fuse box. Carefully remove your existing thermostat or cover from the wall. On most thermostats, you can take off the thermostat by grasping and gently pulling. Some thermostats may have screws, buttons or clasps.

What you should typically see is 18-gauge solid core wire. The most common configuration is five wires; however, you could see as few as two, and as many as ten.

What are signs you have an incompatible system?

Here are some signs you may have a high voltage or line voltage system in your home.

1. Your thermostat has thick black or red wires connected by nuts.

2. Your thermostat is labeled 120v or 240v.

3. Your thermostat has stranded wires.

If you see any of these things, this smart thermostat will not work with your wiring. Honeywell Home has thermostats that do work with line voltage systems; however, this thermostat is not compatible.

Do you have a C-Wire?

C-Wires are required on all Honeywell Home Smart Thermostats.

  • To find an unused C-Wire, you will need to remove your existing thermostat wall plate. Look at the bundle of wires coming from the wall. Note: You may have to pull the bundle of wires out from the wall to find the unused wire.
  • If you do not have a C-Wire or extra wire in the bundle but your old thermostat does use Y and G wires, you will need to purchase a C-Wire Adapter for this Smart Thermostat to be compatible with your home.

    1.
    This came with a broken wire clip, old wire tips stuck in two clips, and missing labels. This was a broken customer return dropped straight into the mail and shipped to me without even checking if it needed to be renewed. Edit: 7/10/2023. The 2nd unit didn't... See more
    This came with a broken wire clip, old wire tips stuck in two clips, and missing labels. This was a broken customer return dropped straight into the mail and shipped to me without even checking if it needed to be renewed.

    Edit: 7/10/2023. The 2nd unit didn't have the protective film that 1st one did, but it was in perfect condition with all of the labels and no broken parts. The install was very easy, but it turned on and told me that the inside temp was 61°, then that sank down to 52° within a few minutes. The actual temp was 75° and climbing. It showed 100% humidity. I factory reset it and completed the simple setup and registration process, but there was no change. Sending this one back. The touchscreen seems a little insensitive all over, otherwise this seems to be a great thermostat. Adjusting rating to reflect the product and not the horrible users that are sending broken items as renewed.

    Edit: The 3rd thermostat, also "renewed" had a whole piece of plastic, including one plastic clip, broken off, so sending this one back too. The picture is attached for detail and to clarify the misinformation about the clips breaking because they're delicate. Significant pressure is needed to force the small round bump on the underside of the clip far enough into the metal pincers to force them open wider than the wire that would be pinched in-between them. The pincers will never be wider than the clip, so almost all of the pressure will be transferred directly to the metal, not to the plastic clip hinge. That is assuming that the instructions are followed and the pressure is applied to the end of the clip and not somewhere in the middle. It also makes it obvious that the clips are necessary, and broken clips are not "renewed".

    Edit: 7/23/2023. The 4th renewed thermostat is physically unbroken and seems to be working perfectly. The touchscreen functionality isn't as perfect as a smartphone's, but otherwise, this is everything it promises to be. Alexa connection required little more than adding the tstat in the Total Connect Comfort app and enabling that skill in the Alexa app.

    The thermostat itself works. There are several pain points however:

    5) The website to adjust the schedule is a major pain and the scheduling system is not flexible. You can only change the temperature 4 times a day. I'd prefer to ramp down temperature incrementally towards bedtime.

  • JT-NY
    4.0 out of 5 starsVerified Purchase
    It's a great thermostat, after a few tries.
    Reviewed in the United States on May 31, 2023
    0:41
    I've wanted to upgrade to these thermostats for some time, but the cost was a deterrent. Once I found these "recertified" units, the price was right and I bought two of them: upstairs and downstairs zones. About me: I'm probably an intermediate to advanced... See more
    I've wanted to upgrade to these thermostats for some time, but the cost was a deterrent. Once I found these "recertified" units, the price was right and I bought two of them: upstairs and downstairs zones. About me: I'm probably an intermediate to advanced DIY'er, and I generally troubleshoot and fix stuff without resorting to calling support or returning stuff unless they're really defective.

    The short version: my experience with these recertified units was not so great; both units were defective out-of-the-box. Thankfully I was able replace both thermostats, and after some additional elbow grease, everything is working properly. So I'm happy. Ultimately everything worked out, and I would absolutely recommend these; you may just need to plan on some follow-though before everything works as smoothly as it should. I am a little disappointed in the quality control of these "recertified" devices.

    The long version: as I explained earlier, I bought two thermostats. The downstairs unit installation was straight forward. I installed and wired the back panel, and then snapped on the thermostat. It booted up and was pretty easy to set up. The touch screen was not as responsive as I would have liked, but I assumed I had cold or dry hands or something. More on this later.

    Upstairs, I disassembled and removed my old thermostat and prepared to install my second RTH9585WF. Right out of the box, this one had the back-panel attached (unlike the first one). After separating the back-panel, a little piece of plastic fell out: it was the clip that anchors one of the control wires! And there was no way to work around this because it was the "Y" wire is the first stage heat, and I only have one stage heat. If it was the "Y2", I could have just ignored it, but given the damaged clip, there was no way around this. So I reinstalled the old thermostat, and return/replaced the second unit. Delivery time: 2-days, and then I got a message that it was only shipped on the day it should have been delivered, so it arrived late on day three. No big deal, but I’d rather not have the expectation. Repeat the removal of the old thermostat and installation of the new one. Everything went well until I got to the registration of this second thermostat in my online Total Comfort account (so I can remote control the device): I couldn't register it because it was already registered in someone else's account! (seriously!) I googled an 800 number for Honeywell support and a very helpful rep got the issue resolved. I was lucky because I got in touch right before they closed on a Saturday; I’d have had to wait until Monday had I not gotten in touch when I did. Thankfully the support rep was very competent, understood the issue and knew how to fix it. Sher texted me a link that allowed me to share my phone’s camera, allowing her to live view the thermostat. This allowed her to validate the device's MAC and CRC, and compare with whatever she was seeing on her end. It took about 15-20 minutes, and then everything was resolved and worked as it should have. Close the chapter on the upstairs thermostat.

    Back to the downstairs thermostat. While tinkering with it, I had a lot of difficulty with the touch screen (see the attached video.) The upper third of the touch screen was very unresponsive. I originally thought I had dry hands or something, but after seeing how responsively and well the second thermostat's touch screen worked, I realized the first one was defective. I tried cleaning it, made sure there was no protective film, etc. No improvement. So I had no choice but to send it back. This time, the replacement arrived overnight, and I simply swapped out the thermostat (didn't even replace the back-panel.) I'm happy to report the initial setup worked flawlessly and this unit is working the way it should.

    So in conclusion, I ordered two of these recertified RTH9585WF thermostats, and both were defective. The first replacement required Honeywell support to deregister the device from its previous owner so I could use it, and the second replacement was flawless. In other words, only one of the four recertified devices installed and functioned as it should have. A 25% success rate is not so great. Total time to get this done should have been an hour, and it took a week. Just imagine if I was paying an HVAC person to do this, and they had to come back twice, it would have cost a fortune! If you're a DIY'er, I recommend them, and just bear in mind that it might not go as smoothly as it should. However, if your time is worth more than the hundred dollars that you're saving on each of these by getting "recertified" devices, then just cough up the cash and get new ones. I wanted to put three stars because of the poor “recertified” quality control, but I settled on four stars because in the end thermostats are working well, becauase Honeywell support was fantastic, and because Amazon's return policy made it very easy to replace the defective units.
